# Approach
We have m money and c children.
**Let's give a dollar to every child.**
Now, **we have m-c money** and first condition is satisfied.

Considering second and third case, we just have to maximise the number of children with 8 dollars. **Starting from the first child till the second last child, give them 7 dollars if we have 7 or more dollars.**

We have distributed money properly so far, now we check the last child. **If we have exactly 7 dollars left, give them to the last child and all the children have exactly 8 dollars.**

**If we have exactly 3 dollars and if all other children have 8 dollars, then for not giving 4 candies to a child, the number of children with 8 candies would get reduced by 1**, as we will not give 4 candies to the last child, and it would disturb the count of 8 candies of the previous child. 

**Apart from 3 or 7 dollars left, any other amount of dollars left won't change the number of children with 8 dollars.** 



# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int distMoney(int money, int children) {
        int ans=0;
        if(children>money)return -1;

        vector<int> v(children,1);  //Give each child a dollar
        money-=children;

        for(int i=0;i<children-1;i++){
            if(money>6){
                ans++;
                v[i]+=7;     //Give 7 dollarrs to children if possible
                money-=7;
            }
        }
        if(money==7)ans++;    //for the last child if we have 7 dollars left

        else if (money==3){ 
            if(v[children-2]==8){
                ans--;       //if we are left with 3 dollars and all
            }                //other children have 8 dollars, it would
        }                    //disturb our count of children with 8 dollars        
        return ans;
    }
};
```
