# Approach
The solution first subtracts the number of children from the total amount of money. If the resulting money is negative, it returns -1 as it's not possible to distribute the money. The function then calculates the remainder of dividing the remaining money by 7 and the division result.

Three cases are considered for returning the result:

If the division result equals the number of children and the remainder is 0, it means each child will receive an equal amount, so the function returns the division result.
If the division result is one less than the number of children and the remainder is 3, it indicates that one child will receive 3 extra units. In this case, the function returns the division result minus 1.
If none of the above cases match, the function returns the minimum of children - 1 and the division result.
This solution is designed to ensure fair distribution of money among the children according to the specified conditions.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(1)

- Space complexity: O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int distMoney(int money, int children) {
        money -= children; // Distribute equally among children, subtracting the number of children
        if (money < 0) {
            return -1; // Not enough money for each child
        }

        int rem = money % 7; // Calculate the remaining money after distributing in multiples of 7
        int div = money / 7; // Calculate the quotient (number of groups of 7)

        // Check for conditions where distribution is possible
        if (div == children && rem == 0) {
            return div; // Money can be equally distributed among children
        }
        if (div == children - 1 && rem == 3) {
            return div - 1; // Distribute to all but one child, with 3 extra money
        }

        // Return the minimum of distributing among all but one child or dividing into groups of 7
        return Math.min(children - 1, div);
    }
}

```

