# Intuition & Approach
- first handle cases we can determine in O(1)
- iteratively accumulate Eighters and then handle edge cases

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n) (since we process `money` in chunks of 7)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int distMoney(int money, int children) {

        // check for not enough money for every kid to get $1
        if (money < children) {
            return -1;
        }
        // check for not enough money for even a single kid to receive $8
        if (money < children + 7) {
            return 0;
        }

        int numEighters = 0;  // what we'll return

        money -= children;  // start by giving each kid $1
        int possibleEighters = children;
        while (money >= 7 && possibleEighters > 0) {  // while we have kids who could be Eighters and we have enough money to make a kid one
            money -= 7;
            ++numEighters;
            --possibleEighters;
        }

        if (money > 0 && possibleEighters == 0) {  // we have to give the leftover money to an Eighter, making them a non-Eighter
            --numEighters;
        } else if (money == 3 && possibleEighters == 1) {  // we have to give or take a dollar from an Eighter to prevent the final non-Eighter from having $4
            --numEighters;
        }
        // else if (money == 0 && possibleEighters == 0)  // we had exactly enough money to make all kids Eighters, so no change in `numEighters`
        // else  // money == 0 && possibleEighters > 0  // no more money, so the rest of the kids stay at $1, and no change in `numEighters`

        return numEighters;

    }
}
```

